<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AMY HARMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Interactive: Former Silicon Graphics Inc. technology wizard Carol Peters and 
Hollywood producer Jeff Apple ("In the Line of Fire") have formed a new media 
company to develop interactive television programming for children. Dubbed 
daVinci Time & Space, the company's goal is to create an interactive 
environment for kids that could contain dozens of games, educational 
experiences, linear movies or TV shows, and advertising from a variety of 
sources -- a kind of electronic Disneyland.At a time when most interactive 
media start-ups are focusing on CD-ROMs or on-line services, where a market 
already exists, daVinci managed to raise nearly $5 million from venture 
capitalists to concentrate solely on the less tangible goal of next-generation 
interactive television. Peters, who developed Silicon Graphics' popular Indigo 
computer, directs daVinci's engineering efforts from an office in San Mateo. 
Apple oversees the creative end from Los Angeles. The two keep in touch via 
(what else?) video conferencing over high-speed phone lines. AMY HARMON 
</P>
