<HEADLINE>
<P>
GLENDALE / BURBANK FOCUS: BURBANK; CANDIDATE REVISES BALLOT STATEMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOCELYN Y. STEWART 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a move that both sides claimed as a victory, a candidate for Burbank 
Municipal Court judge has revised his ballot statement, removing some portions 
that his opponent claimed violated a state elections code, while retaining 
others. 
</P>
<P>
 During a court hearing in Los Angeles on Monday, Superior Court Judge Diane 
Wayne determined that certain passages in attorney Rand Rubin's ballot 
statement were inappropriate, but decided to let him rewrite the document 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
 The decision grew out of a dispute between Rubin and Burbank Municipal Court 
Judge Marion E. Gubler over the legality of Rubin's statement. 
</P>
<P>
 Gubler, who is seeking reelection in the June primary, had accused Rubin of 
violating a California Elections Code section that limits what candidates in 
judicial races may include in statements that are printed on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
 The law limits the statements to a "recitation of the candidate's own personal 
background and qualifications," and prohibits any references to other 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
 Rubin's statement included comments such as the "Burbank court has been 
censured by the California Supreme Court for its mistreatment of our citizens," 
and "the Burbank courts are wasting taxpayer money." Gubler argued that the 
comments were veiled attacks on him. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1984 the Commission on Judicial Performance publicly censured Gubler for 
his "zealous efforts to obtain payment from criminal defendants" to reimburse 
the county for services provided by the public defender's office. The judge was 
also censured for allowing the private sale of guns that had been confiscated 
from convicted criminals. 
</P>
<P>
 Rubin's new statement makes no reference to a censure but does include a 
promise to save taxpayers' money. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm pleased with the ruling," Rubin said. "I consider it a victory. We're 
still getting these issues in front of the voters."  
</P>
<P>
 Gubler said he was satisfied with the outcome of the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 "I won it so I ought to be happy," Gubler said. "That statement didn't belong 
in there in the first place." JOCELYN Y. STEWART 
</P>
</TEXT>
